In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April 10 through April 16, 2011, as National Crime Victims' Rights Week. He acknowledges that while homes and neighborhoods are safer than before, millions of Americans still fall victim to crime each year. The president emphasizes the importance of supporting and assisting those who have been victimized by crime, and highlights the work of crisis counselors, law enforcement professionals, legal advocates, and other service providers in helping victims rebuild their lives. The article also mentions various efforts made by the administration to prevent and address crimes such as cyberbullying, online child sexual exploitation, sexual assault on college campuses, human trafficking, and financial fraud. The president encourages Americans to participate in events that raise awareness of victims' rights and services, and to volunteer to serve victims in their time of need.